[{"id":27155,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>.90</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>BM</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.87</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>BM</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>.93</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>BM</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>.92</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>BM</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"The maximum number of unpaired electrons for transition metals <math><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math><br /><br />or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math><br /><br />Spin only magnetic moment <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></msqrt><mi>BM</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>5</mn><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></msqrt><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>35</mn></msqrt></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>.92</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>BM</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27041,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Both Statement I and Statement II are true"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{k}_{\\mathrm{eq}}=2280$ is for HCHO\n$\\mathrm{k}_{\\text {eq }}=2000$ is for chloral\nBoth data is given in clayden and warren book. $\\mathrm{k}_{\\mathrm{eq}}>1$ because HCHO and chloral are more electrophilic.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (23 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27020,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is true but Statement II is false"],"answer":1,"solution":"Statement I: Cross aldol condensation between two different aldehydes produces four products only if both aldehydes have $\\alpha$-hydrogen atoms. If one aldehyde lacks $\\alpha$-hydrogen (e.g., benzaldehyde and acetaldehyde), only two products are typically formed (one self and one cross). If neither has $\\alpha$-hydrogen, no aldol condensation occurs. Thus, it does not 'always' produce four products. Statement I is false.<br><br>Statement II: Benzaldehyde is an aldehyde and acetophenone is a ketone. Aldehydes are generally more reactive than ketones towards nucleophilic addition reactions due to less steric hindrance and greater electronic deficiency of the carbonyl carbon. Therefore, semicarbazide will react faster with benzaldehyde than with acetophenone. The statement claiming it forms a product with acetophenone only is incorrect. Statement II is false.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27084,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e1716037-93dd-4fe7-af25-714197ea13e1-9893508_1.PNG\" style=\"width: 169px; height: 150px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e2f2a6b4-9b5e-40a6-804a-27538e6b66fa-9893508_2.PNG\" style=\"width: 223px; height: 150px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5512e1c6-0b86-449b-a00f-edc4a80fe5b9-9893508_3.PNG\" style=\"width: 360px; height: 94px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8ee6e327-d804-4d00-ae15-3441476984fd-9893508_4.PNG\" style=\"width: 191px; height: 92px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The cross aldol reaction takes place between isobutyraldehyde and formaldehyde&nbsp;to&nbsp;get hydroxypivaldehyde. On reaction with hydrogen cyanide&nbsp;followed by hydrolysis produces the lactone product.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/048c981b-734c-466b-af6f-d4fa7f8efab3-9893508_5.PNG\" style=\"width: 497px; height: 242px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (24 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27104,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/86948291-90ae-4d35-a10a-4a94722c5fac-image.png\" style=\"width: 602px; height: 138px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/81952f26-e625-4310-8a50-e66763680c4a-image.png\" style=\"width: 414px; height: 94px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0b11d509-dbc4-41b9-b816-bbb13563762d-image.png\" style=\"width: 608px; height: 131px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/12ef7d46-211f-4a03-9e7b-8610b7700f87-image.png\" style=\"width: 418px; height: 91px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Friedel-Craft acylation reaction in&nbsp;benzene&nbsp;takes place. Aluminium chloride is Lewis acid which helps in generating electrophile as shown in first step of reaction.</p><p>This electrophile get substituted in benzene and product (A) is obtained. In next step, Clemmensen&#39;s reduction occur which converts aldehyde or ketone into hydrocarbon.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3aab6398-a5f3-45cb-a64b-7a0a6a310350-lambaaquestion.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 263px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27086,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f59531b4-2b76-4f78-88db-2a5d1da39482-image.png\" style=\"width: 252px; height: 70px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ac979fe6-4922-45b5-917f-ccecaa6baa7c-75a5f7d6-b036-4a97-9546-dd11225e947c-image.png\" style=\"width: 280px; height: 68px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e5960d99-87b9-4dbc-bb1f-d9d4620d1704-image.png\" style=\"width: 292px; height: 70px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ba3b809c-dcb6-4702-8655-8c01de014fbc-image.png\" style=\"width: 270px; height: 80px;\" /></p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Diisobutylaluminium hydride, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AlH</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Bu</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;also known as DIBAL or DIBAL-H, is an exceedingly useful and versatile reducing agent. It is an electrophilic reducing agent, usually employed in selective reductions of esters or nitriles to aldehydes</p><p>So, in first step nitrile group will be reduced to aldehyde group.&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c28ff58c-e447-4e6f-acf7-c45ba8d86919-image.png\" style=\"width: 513px; height: 170px;\" /></p><p>In second step cross aldol condensation reaction will take place which will give mixture of products. Out of which one of the product will be option B.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27032,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/lCq6Mw5q8JPDqNYKyHisrrDNnAx4ofx2_UjVVX5L3pA.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2o9CwKquyG0jDkjQNLEq3bzCV5kHVX6RR73Kwya29Fs.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/r-NTmFQogzdkCT9COLg0s4kZ8UpLrf5eYJlBrWPnpxo.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/tHhfQCia-ldpFFlGVn-w5ZL2wl5j-w-EiKKgnLE_z9k.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fTcSchx5JTQqfUQoxhFdZAY5fekK-RqTkcENAIulG4Y.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (3 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27046,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bvx7GoFyFIhPoII92puMR-dGrYccy3mLIZ9RlpleXKk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/DqlLWnhqyxM6JX4tama1O6VL4mIW7vk1mv-2mLpje2c.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/UgdOEl-mB4ZwyB6IoaCzDjTsd1Ju3bbkOdstKcxTiNk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","\\(\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CHO}\\)"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4tAwID7Lfwtr1xmhTV3OMlMbfsDIBOmvx1aVlkPeeZw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27143,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#8201;</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#8201;</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>&nbsp;have&nbsp;active hydrogen (acidic hydrogen). So,&nbsp;acid base reaction will take place with Grignard reagent.<br /><br /><img height=\"196\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/deb77259-8b50-41c9-839d-e51ec65efbf9-image.png\" width=\"302\" /></p><p><img height=\"196\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1cac9c05-b2d4-4d38-822d-f91f140791cb-image.png\" width=\"335\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27047,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A, B and C only","C and D only","B and C only","A only"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/t1EFpVzElTH1fhMFs-rpI0b_x4vsYHQ7eyy3ErWgWsI.original.fullsize.png\"><br />also gives silver mirror test with ammonical silver nitrate.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27098,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> /acetic acid,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> /acetic anhydride,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CO</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Anhyd</mi><mo>.</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Toluene is oxidised to benzaldehyde in presence of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> /acetic anhydride,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math></p><p>Toluene is converted to&nbsp;benzylidene diacetate&nbsp;and&nbsp;hydrolysis reaction of benzylidene diacetate&nbsp;gives benzaldehyde.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9edbce60-686a-4097-85d4-4bea5da15ff4-image.png\" style=\"width: 550px; height: 175px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27179,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["a Schiff’s base","an enamine","an imine","an amine"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/AagGfUls6Ski_qweMXo6VmNEOVvYb-rsm41SYEaIAe8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":27082,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true","Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true but R is NOT the correct explanation of A"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>For Assertion:&nbsp;The acetals are unstable in the presence of aqueous solutions of acid because they undergo hydrolysis in the presence of acidic conditions to produce the parent aldehyde or ketone or alcohols. But are stable and do not undergo hydrolysis in the presence of a base or under neutral conditions.</p><p>Hence assertion is correct.</p><p>For reason: Alkoxide ion <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><msup><mi>RO</mi><mo>&#8211;</mo></msup><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;is not considered a good leaving group</p><p>Hence reason must be false.</p><p>So, the correct option is A</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27149,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<p><img height=\"87\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/310afcce-10be-43ec-940c-00db18cfc1c8-image.png\" width=\"230\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"80\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9641280b-a179-46b6-b158-2f20a8f66a8f-image.png\" width=\"231\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"135\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/07f4b3a5-7bb4-4867-b1ec-306d1ee57b23-image.png\" width=\"162\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"133\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c966cc3a-2791-430f-9b63-1cb26916572b-image.png\" width=\"163\" /></p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eff8b53f-bb86-4d23-bf6a-225d6620601c-1559375a-bf8a-436d-9c12-e6012da49d3c-image.png\" style=\"width: 556px; height: 138px;\" /><br /><br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Intramolecular aldol condensation<br /><br /><img height=\"380\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f833ea55-0915-48e6-a840-7a69054bd46f-image.png\" width=\"273\" /><br /><br /><img height=\"400\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4469dfc4-1a1c-4284-babc-c136b2620c0d-image.png\" width=\"259\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27131,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/727034c2-f87f-4240-aa35-c9ff30abc6c3-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 104px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6f8cc3c4-6435-4f84-be88-0b6fc6b2d9a8-image.png\" style=\"width: 402px; height: 106px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4159a267-278d-4f70-9400-a785c11403db-image.png\" style=\"width: 440px; height: 97px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a1c06898-3148-429a-90f4-0bf3acec4a53-image.png\" style=\"width: 520px; height: 60px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>B will be ketone as it gives tertiary alcohol after reaction with grignard while A will be aldehyde which produces secondary alcohol after reaction with grignard reagent.&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/050585e9-d9e0-4396-a754-1f4cc85df7f7-image.png\" style=\"width: 525px; height: 390px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27147,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/uHntVp39EZXmU5to9X4Oeeo9-hbSRW0wx1030PwiVYY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Agu3qmQPs5Pv88pAml4pmHUg9RnQCMegIffOwAXRXqE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/F-C1pk3AuXL8ByebYziUbGVC_u9wGaps3bErasZNszA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/KiVTj9u6JP9tqI8JMmFgc3u5CPDdAWzCydoqR4T8GzY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/j0v1ShU_N_M463UnAJMu6B06yhyuIrtQOpruT-xT2f4.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\r\n\r\nLiAlH $_{4}$ is a nucleophilic reducing agent, hence it will reduce $-\\mathrm{COOH}$ to $\\mathrm{CH}_{2} \\mathrm{OH},-\\mathrm{CO}$ to $-\\mathrm{CHOH}$ and $-\\mathrm{NO}_{2}$ to\r\n\r\n$\\mathrm{NH}_{2}$ but does not reduce $\\mathrm{C}=\\mathrm{C}$ linkage.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27126,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["(I)-(Q), (II)-(R) and (III)-(P)","(I)-(P), (II)-(Q) and (III)-(R)","(I)-(R), (II)-(P) and (III)-(Q)","(I)-(R), (II)-(Q) and (III)-(P)"],"answer":2,"solution":"<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 500px;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/52ab7133-1e59-45aa-bd63-284c92203f92-image.png\" style=\"width: 337px; height: 179px;\" /></td>\t\t\t<td>Gatterman-Koach reaction</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/610ade81-2f08-4913-9924-931e06